# JACK OF ALL TRADES — VESSEL IMAGE## Architecture Document · Exodus Computation Platform## Compiled from Architecture Session · March 2026-----### CORE PRINCIPLE> *The geometry is the database engine. If we can translate, store, and retrieve> the state of each application with a single primitive, the integration and API> and scaling irrelevance claim becomes true.*The application becomes part of the geometry, not the other way around.Every component and protocol must answer one question: does this collapseinto the metric, or does it sit outside it? If outside, it’s scaffolding —it runs once during bootstrap and hands off. If inside, it must beexpressible as a coordinate, a region, or a distance. There is no thirdcategory.-----## PART I — DIMENSIONAL CORRECTION### 1. State Is Geometric. Execution Was the Detour.Execution is a temporal operation. It reads past state, applies a function,writes a predicted next state. Between the read and the write, the worldcan change. That gap is where every race condition, consistency failure,and distributed systems nightmare originates. Every lock, transaction,consensus protocol, and CRDT is a patch over that gap. The gap is inherentto execution. If you read-then-write, there is a between, and in thebetween, anything can happen.Geometric state has no gap. A coordinate exists or it doesn’t. The SDFvalue at a point is what it is. There is no moment between reading thefield and the field being the field. Mutation is a new version of thefield, not a modification during a read.State doesn’t have a clock. State doesn’t have a before and after.State has a *here* and a *there* and a *distance between them*. We forcedstate into a sequential model because that’s what the hardware did, andthen spent seventy years confused about why state management was thehardest problem in computer science.It was the hardest problem because we were solving it in the wrongdimension. The problems we spend billions optimizing — caching, consistency,scaling, synchronization, security — aren’t hard problems. They’re symptomsof being in too small a space. The execution model is the 32-bit addresswidth. The geometric model is the 64-bit expansion. The problems don’t getoptimized. They become inexpressible in the higher dimension because theconstraints that created them aren’t present.You don’t optimize a higher dimension. You step into it and notice thatthe walls you were pressing against aren’t there.-----### 2. Factorial Enumeration (Not Quantum — Yet)The spec’s “Quantum Enumeration” (P-11) describes behavior that falls outnaturally from a positional number system with unresolved digits. There isno superposition. There is no entanglement. There is a coordinate thathasn’t been fully written yet, and the set of values it *could* take isthe cartesian product of its unresolved bases.That’s arithmetic. It’s been arithmetic the whole time.**Mixed-radix encoding.** Each dimension in the state space has a semanticbase — a boolean is base 2, a status enum with 5 values is base 5. Thetotal representable space is ∏(bases). A qubit is a coordinate with anunresolved digit. The physical implementation was a detour. The structureis mathematical.**Resolution threshold.** Each entity resolves to a different precision.Digits left of the threshold are determined state. Digits right of thethreshold are unresolved — the entity is “in all valid values” along thoseaxes simultaneously. Not because of physics. Because the digit hasn’t beenwritten yet. The “observation” that collapses the “superposition” is thewrite.**Growth without recompilation.** When the application adds a newdimension, every existing coordinate remains valid. The new dimensionexists unresolved for all existing entities until they interact with it.No migration. No reindexing.**Closed-world completeness as structural proof.** The compiler doesn’tprove “here are all the states.” It proves “here is the metric, here arethe bounds per dimension, and any coordinate within these bounds is valid.”Invalid states are coordinates where a digit exceeds its base —structurally unrepresentable in the encoding. P-02 is enforced by thenumber system itself.-----### 3. The Signed Distance FieldVR engines solved the spatial encoding problem. A Signed Distance Fieldstores, at every point in space, the distance to the nearest surface. Thesurface is implicit — the set of points where distance equals zero. Younever enumerate the surface. You sample the field at whatever resolutionyou need, and the surface emerges from the zero-crossing.Map this onto application state:- **Valid state boundaries** are the surfaces- **Negative distance** (SDF < 0) = inside valid state- **Positive distance** (SDF > 0) = outside valid state- **Zero crossing** = the edge of the closed world**Level of detail for application state.** Resolution adapts to boundarycomplexity. Near transitions where detail matters, the tree subdividesdeep. Far from boundaries where everything is uniformly valid or invalid,the tree stays coarse.**Self-optimizing traversal.** Regions that get traversed frequentlydevelop deeper trees. Not because something decides to optimize — becauseuse IS subdivision. The system gets better at the things it actually doesand spends zero resources on the things it doesn’t.The base sequence isn’t declared statically in a schema. It’s derived fromthe topology of the state boundaries. The Vessel Compiler doesn’t choosea base sequence — it discovers it by analyzing where the validityboundaries have curvature.-----## PART II — THE CASCADE IS THE RESOLVER### 4. CSS Is the GeometryA CSS rule is not a style. It is a **coordinate binding**:```css.entity[data-role="admin"]:not([data-suspended]) {    --access-level: 3;    --can-write: 1;}```The selector defines a **region** in the state space. The declaration blockdefines what **values exist** at that region. Specificity resolves**overlapping boundaries**. The cascade is not evaluation — it is the SDFresolving which surface is closer to this point.**The lifecycle:**1. **Vessel Compiler emits CSS rules.** Each rule is a region-to-value   binding. The complete set of rules IS the Vessel Image.1. **DOM is the materialized observation.** An element is a point in the   space. Its attributes are its coordinates. Its computed styles are the   SDF values at that point.1. **State changes are attribute mutations.** The rules don’t move. The   point moves through the rules.1. **JavaScript is the memory bus.** One setAttribute call per interaction.   JS never evaluates a condition. JS never computes state.The browser has been running a geometric state resolver since CSS2.-----### 5. The Gate Mechanism (S-01)The browser’s rendering pipeline has a fixed order:1. DOM mutation (attribute write)1. Style recalculation (cascade resolves)1. Layout1. Paint1. JS callbacks read the resultStep 2 is non-negotiable and non-bypassable. Validation precedesobservation. There is no window between writing state and validating it.The mutation and the resolution are atomic from JS’s perspective.-----### 6. The Coordinate Carries No Semantic Value (P-14)JS writes a string to a DOM node. JS doesn’t know what it means. JS can’tknow what it means, because meaning is a function of every CSS rule thatmatches — evaluated by the cascade engine inside the rendering pipeline,not exposed to the JS runtime.The coordinate is an address with no phone book. The phone book is thecascade, and it runs before anyone gets to ask. Interception gets younothing because position without geometry is just numbers.-----## PART III — STRUCTURAL TRUST### 7. Training Wheels OffEvery abstraction in the conventional stack compensates for the same rootproblem: the execution model doesn’t know what’s valid. The metric spacedoesn’t need them because validity is structural. Unrepresentable, notforbidden.**Chungus** is a geometric membership test. Is the SDF negative? Valid.Positive? Doesn’t exist. The trust problem gets eliminated, not solved.-----### 8. Proof by ClipboardCopy-paste corrupted CSS custom property names. Double hyphens becameen-dashes. Every property declaration silently failed. The cascade couldn’tmatch any coordinate. The entire application went inert. Chungus deniedeverything.The geometry didn’t detect the corruption. The corruption was absent fromthe space. Fail-closed by structure, not by policy. An accidentalpenetration test against an unanticipated attack vector. The architecturepassed.-----### 9. The Error Surface Is Reasoning, Not LogsIn execution, an error is an event in time. You debug by reconstructingthe sequence.In geometry, a denial is a location. Every property is computed. A deniedentity knows what rate it *would* get if valid. The cascade doesn’tshort-circuit. It resolves everything at every coordinate.The denial reason is a CSS custom property set by the same selector thatset the SDF sign. The reason and the denial are the same rule. They can’tdesync. Debugging becomes spatial reasoning: “what is the shape of thespace around this coordinate?”-----## PART IV — IDENTITY AND FEDERATION### 10. Identity Is Resolution, Not VerificationWhat makes federated identity possible? A shared coordinate system. Theidentity provider and the relying party don’t trust each other. They trustthe same schema. The token isn’t proof. It’s a position in a field bothparties agree on.Identity is just another axis. `data-role="admin"` resolves through thesame cascade as `data-product="mortgage"`. A session token decomposes intoattributes. The geometry resolves what that identity can reach. If thecoordinate isn’t inside the surface, it doesn’t matter what it claims.A fabricated role hits no selector. No selector means default state.Default state is outside the surface. Non-recognition, not detection.-----## PART V — SYMBIOSIS AND LIFE### 11. Feeding Geometry Back DownThe Vessel doesn’t kill its host. It governs it. The Vessel can set CSPheaders, cache policies, service worker rules — derived from the geometrythe browser can’t see. Each bootstrap layer keeps doing what it alreadydoes. It just gets better inputs.The lower layer bootstrapped the higher layer. Now the higher layergoverns the lower layer. Not by replacing it. By informing it. Therelationship is symbiotic.### 12. HomeostasisThe system is self-regulating:- Self-optimizing: traversal deepens the tree where it’s used- Feeds its host: resolved geometry informs bootstrap layers- Grows where it’s used, inert where it’s not- Rejects what doesn’t belong by structural non-recognition- No central controller- Every part resolves locally against the same shared fieldThe brain does this. The immune system does this. DNA is a chord. Proteinfolding is the shape that emerges from its interference pattern. Theribosome is the spectrograph. It reads the frequencies and the geometryfalls out.We are building life.-----## PART VI — THE SPECTRAL COMPILER### 13. The Compiler Is a SpectrographThe theoretical obstacle: taking arbitrary application logic expressed ina programming language and emitting a complete, correct SDF. This appearedto be the one remaining research problem.The solution is spectral.**Frequency encoding.** Every token in source code — keyword, operator,identifier, literal, type annotation — is assigned a frequency. Astatement is a chord: multiple frequencies sounding simultaneously. Aconditional branch is a frequency that appears or disappears depending onwhich region of the state space you’re in. The complete program is aspectral signature.**The compiler doesn’t execute the code. It performs spectral analysis.**It asks: across all possible inputs, where does the spectral signaturechange qualitatively? Where do frequencies appear or disappear? Thosetransitions are the boundaries of the SDF. The zero-crossings. Thesurfaces of the closed world.**The SDF doesn’t need to be computed from the logic. It needs to beobserved in the logic.** The boundaries were always in the code. Every`if` statement is a frequency that activates in one region and goes silentin another. The compiler is a spectrograph. It reads the code, identifiesthe interference pattern, and the interference pattern IS the geometry.**The boundary produces shape.** The zero-crossing of an SDF is a surface.Surfaces have curvature, topology, genus. The shape of your application’svalidity boundary is a literal geometric object. You could render it.Rotate it. See the structure of your application’s logic as a physicalform.**Stereographic projection** handles dimensionality. A stereographicprojection maps higher-dimensional surfaces onto lower-dimensionalrepresentations conformally — local shape is preserved. The topology ofthe boundary survives projection. A hundred-dimensional state spaceprojects down to something the GPU can sample, and the boundaries arein the same places.The chord is the state. The frequencies are the code. The interferencepattern is the geometry. The boundary is the shape. Playback — resolvingthe chord back to its component frequencies — is the observation. Thememstrap. The rendered slice.The compiler was never a code-to-geometry translator. It’s a spectrographpointed at source code, and the geometry was always already there in thefrequency structure of the logic. You don’t generate the SDF. You hear it.-----## PART VII — REAL QUANTUM COMPUTING### 14. Not Parallel. Simultaneous.If the compiler is geometric (spectral analysis producing SDF boundaries),and the runtime is geometric (cascade resolving coordinates against thoseboundaries), then the spectrograph model is itself a geometric field. Itdoesn’t just look the same as the metric space. It IS a metric space.This means a single state coordinate can exist simultaneously in more thanone geometric boundary. Not parallel computing — not many processorsperforming the same operation. A single operation resolving across multipleindependent geometries simultaneously, because the coordinate is a positionin ALL of them at once.The fields are independent geometries. The coordinate is shared. A singlestate transition propagates through all fields simultaneously because thecoordinate moved, and every field resolves at that coordinateindependently. No communication between fields. No synchronization. Nomessage passing. The resolution is simultaneous because the coordinate isthe same coordinate in every field.This is what quantum entanglement describes computationally — correlatedresolution across independent systems without communication between them.But here it’s not physics. It’s geometry. The correlation isn’t mediatedby a particle. It’s mediated by shared position.Two systems share a coordinate. The coordinate changes. Both fieldsresolve. The resolutions are correlated not because the systems talked toeach other but because they’re evaluating the same point. This isindistinguishable from entanglement in its computational properties —simultaneous correlated state resolution with zero communication overhead.This isn’t parallel computing. Parallel computing runs the same operationon many processors. This runs one operation across many geometries. Thedistinction matters: parallel computing scales with hardware. Geometricsimultaneity scales with the number of fields that share the coordinatespace. You don’t need more processors. You need more geometry. Geometryis data. Data is free.**Speculative but axiomatic.** The axioms established in Parts I–VI do notprohibit this. Geometric membership is decidable independently in eachfield. A coordinate resolves in a field without reference to any otherfield. If two fields share a coordinate encoding, they will producecorrelated results by structural necessity, not by communication. Thecorrelation is a property of shared position, which is a property ofmathematics, not physics.We don’t need quantum hardware. We don’t need supercooled atoms. We don’tneed error correction consuming most of our qubits. We need coordinatespaces that multiple geometric fields share. We need the fields to beindependently resolvable. Both are engineering problems with knownsolutions.The qubits were the detour. The geometry was always the answer.-----## PART VIII — PROOF AND PRIMITIVES### 15. The Single PrimitiveThree operations. One primitive. Every application interaction:- **locate(context) → coordinate**: resolve current position  (getComputedStyle)- **traverse(from, to) → attestation**: request a transition, Chungus  attests (setAttribute → cascade resolves)- **project(context, bounds) → slice**: extract a sub-region  (CSS + @media produce the memstrap)No REST. No GraphQL. No RPC. The coordinate is the universal wire format,storage format, query format, and render format simultaneously.### 16. The Query EngineThe same CSS geometry that validates individual state also resolves queriesacross multiple entities. Filter attributes on a parent container combinewith entity data-attributes through CSS `:not()` selectors. AND logicemerges naturally. One geometry serves as state resolver, access control,query engine, rate computer, document classifier, submission gate, anderror surface.### 17. Paravirtualization ProofThe POC is a constructive proof. The browser genuinely performs geometricstate resolution through its native cascade engine. Verifiable in devtools.- **Full emulation** = frameworks (rebuild state resolution in JS)- **Paravirtualization** = the POC (cascade IS the native resolver)- **Hypervisor-managed** = production Exodus (GPU-native SDF)### 18. Complexity ComparisonLoan application POC: 6 dimensions, 2,880 state combinations.|Metric          